ChatGPT said:

The error comes from a misuse of add_headers() in the httr::VERB() function.

The issue is this part:

r
add_headers(
  'Authorization' = paste0('Bearer ', tmdb_key),
  content_type("application/octet-stream"), 
  accept("application/json")
)

The functions content_type() and accept() already produce headers. You cannot combine them like this inside add_headers().

Solution: Write all headers explicitly as character strings inside add_headers().

Correct version:

r
response <- VERB("GET", url, query = queryString, add_headers(
  Authorization = paste0('Bearer ', tmdb_key),
  `Content-Type` = "application/octet-stream",
  Accept = "application/json"
))

Notice:

  1. Authorization, Content-Type, Accept are header names written as plain character strings.

  2. Backticks `...` are used for Content-Type because of the hyphen.

  3. add_headers() takes key-value pairs where both sides are strings.

This will fix the is.character(headers) error.

ChatGPT said:

Thanks for clarifying. Here's a general-purpose function that takes as input:

  • A function you already wrote (let’s call it get_tmdb_df)

  • That function must accept page as one of its arguments and return a data.frame with a column total_pages.

  • This function will iterate from page 1 to total_pages, query all pages, and bind the results into a single dataframe.

✅ Your Desired Loop Function:

r
library(dplyr)

get_all_pages <- function(get_tmdb_df, ...) {
  # First request, page 1
  first_df <- get_tmdb_df(page = 1, ...)
  
  # Extract total pages
  total_pages <- first_df$total_pages[1]
  
  # Collect results
  all_data <- list(first_df)
  
  # Loop through remaining pages if more than 1
  if (total_pages > 1) {
    for (p in 2:total_pages) {
      df <- get_tmdb_df(page = p, ...)
      all_data[[p]] <- df
    }
  }
  
  # Combine all into one data.frame
  bind_rows(all_data)
}

🚨 Assumptions:

  1. get_tmdb_df(page = ..., ...) returns a data.frame with columns for the data plus a total_pages column.

  2. All pages share the same columns and can be row-binded safely.

  3. tmdb_key is handled inside get_tmdb_df, so you don’t need to pass it here.

📄 Example Usage:

r

get_tmdb_df <- function(page, queryString) {

    Authorization = paste0('Bearer ', tmdb_key),
    `Content-Type` = "application/json",

  ))
  data <- content(response, "parsed")$results
  df <- bind_rows(data) %>% mutate(total_pages = content(response, "parsed")$total_pages)
  return(df)
}

You said:
for the get all page code. add condition that if total_pages is null, lengthzero, just return the first df
ChatGPT said:

Got it. Here's the revised get_all_pages function with your requested condition:
If total_pages is NULL, length-zero, or missing, it will just return the first dataframe without looping.

✅ Final get_all_pages Function:

r
library(dplyr)

get_all_pages <- function(get_tmdb_df, ...) {
  # First request (always page 1)
  first_df <- get_tmdb_df(page = 1, ...)
  
  # Defensive check for total_pages
  total_pages <- first_df$total_pages[1]
  
  if (is.null(total_pages) || length(total_pages) == 0 || is.na(total_pages)) {
    return(first_df)
  }
  
  # Collect results
  all_data <- list(first_df)
  
  # Loop through remaining pages if more than 1
  if (total_pages > 1) {
    for (p in 2:total_pages) {
      df <- get_tmdb_df(page = p, ...)
      all_data[[p]] <- df
    }
  }
  
  bind_rows(all_data)
}

🚨 Why this works:

  • is.null(total_pages) handles NULL

  • length(total_pages) == 0 handles empty

  • is.na(total_pages) handles missing values (e.g., API failure)

  • If any of these are true, it just returns first_df immediately.

how to kick something out of a list
ChatGPT said:

🔧 To remove elements from a list in R, you can do it in several ways depending on what you mean by "kick out":

1️⃣ By Index

If you know the position (e.g., 2nd element):

r
my_list <- list(a = 1, b = 2, c = 3)
my_list[2] <- NULL  # removes the 2nd element ("b")
my_list
# $a
# [1] 1
# $c
# [1] 3

2️⃣ By Name

If you know the name:

r
my_list[["b"]] <- NULL  # removes element named "b"
my_list

3️⃣ By Condition

If you want to remove based on value or condition:

r
my_list <- list(a = 1, b = 2, c = 3)
my_list <- my_list[!(sapply(my_list, function(x) x == 2))]
my_list
# $a
# [1] 1
# $c
# [1] 3

📝 Summary Table:

ActionCode Example
Remove by indexmy_list[2] <- NULL
Remove by namemy_list[["b"]] <- NULL
Remove by conditionmy_list[...condition...]

🔍 Problem:

Your error comes from trying to force nested lists of inconsistent lengths into a tibble directly.
as_tibble() expects all columns to be the same length, but genres and belongs_to_collection are nested lists with different sizes (length 2 vs. 4 in your error).

flatten() does not handle nested lists within columns correctly for tibbles.

✅ Recommended Solution:

Do not convert the full fromJSON response into a tibble immediately. Instead:

  1. Pick the fields you want manually.

  2. Convert only those fields into a flat tibble.

🔧 Example Fix:

r
library(httr)
library(jsonlite)
library(dplyr)
library(tibble)

get_movie_details <- function(movie_id) {
  
  url <- paste0("https://api.themoviedb.org/3/movie/", movie_id)
  
  queryString <- list(
    language = "en-US"
  )
  
  response <- VERB("GET", url, query = queryString,
                   add_headers(
                     Authorization = paste0('Bearer ', tmdb_key),
                     `Content-Type` = "application/octet-stream",
                     Accept = "application/json"
                   ))
  
  movie_det <- fromJSON(content(response, "text", encoding = "UTF-8"))
  
  # Manually extract key fields only, ignoring nested structures
  out <- tibble(
    id = movie_det$id,
    title = movie_det$title,
    popularity = movie_det$popularity,
    revenue = movie_det$revenue,
    vote_average = movie_det$vote_average,
    vote_count = movie_det$vote_count,
    release_date = movie_det$release_date,
    poster_path = movie_det$poster_path
  )
  
  return(out)
}

🔍 Why?

Nested fields like genres are lists of dataframes, not scalars. Either extract them separately (e.g., genres$name as a string of names) or leave them out.

If you want genres as a comma-separated string:

r
genres <- paste(sapply(movie_det$genres, `[[`, "name"), collapse = ", ")

Then include genres = genres in your tibble().

🚩 Remove append_to_response:

That parameter does not accept those values. Only specific endpoints like credits,videos are allowed.
Your extra fields like popularity, revenue are already included in /movie/{movie_id}.

📝 Summary:

  • Don't flatten() or tibble() directly on deeply nested JSON.

  • Extract only what you need.

  • Convert nested list-columns to strings manually if desired.

Below is a robust function that flattens nested fields into readable columns (e.g., concatenated strings), preserves scalars, and outputs a clean 1-row dataframe.

✅ Final get_movie_details() for Your Structure

r
library(httr)
library(jsonlite)
library(dplyr)
library(tibble)

get_movie_details <- function(movie_id) {
  
  url <- paste0("https://api.themoviedb.org/3/movie/", movie_id)
  
  response <- VERB("GET", url,
                   query = list(language = "en-US"),
                   add_headers(
                     Authorization = paste0('Bearer ', tmdb_key),
                     `Content-Type` = "application/json",
                     Accept = "application/json"
                   ))
  
  movie_det <- fromJSON(content(response, "text", encoding = "UTF-8"))
  
  # Flatten nested fields as comma-separated text
  genres <- if (!is.null(movie_det$genres)) {
    paste(movie_det$genres$name, collapse = ", ")
  } else {
    NA_character_
  }
  
  production_countries <- if (!is.null(movie_det$production_countries)) {
    paste(movie_det$production_countries$name, collapse = ", ")
  } else {
    NA_character_
  }
  
  spoken_languages <- if (!is.null(movie_det$spoken_languages)) {
    paste(movie_det$spoken_languages$english_name, collapse = ", ")
  } else {
    NA_character_
  }
  
  production_companies <- if (!is.null(movie_det$production_companies)) {
    paste(movie_det$production_companies$name, collapse = ", ")
  } else {
    NA_character_
  }
  
  # Create a 1-row tibble
  df <- tibble(
    id = movie_det$id,
    title = movie_det$title,
    popularity = movie_det$popularity,
    revenue = movie_det$revenue,
    vote_average = movie_det$vote_average,
    vote_count = movie_det$vote_count,
    release_date = movie_det$release_date,
    poster_path = movie_det$poster_path,
    genres = genres,
    production_countries = production_countries,
    spoken_languages = spoken_languages,
    production_companies = production_companies,
    status = movie_det$status,
    tagline = movie_det$tagline,
    budget = movie_det$budget,
    runtime = movie_det$runtime,
    imdb_id = movie_det$imdb_id,
    homepage = movie_det$homepage,
    origin_country = paste(movie_det$origin_country, collapse = ", "),
    total_pages = 1 # For your loop compatibility
  )
  
  return(df)
}

🔍 Why this works for you:

  • Nested lists (genres, production_countries, etc.) are flattened into readable string columns.

  • All columns are scalar now — no lists, no data.frames inside.

  • total_pages = 1 makes it compatible with your existing get_all_pages() loop.

  • The result is a tibble with 1 row and clean columns.

✅ Example Output (Column Names):

bash
id | title | popularity | revenue | ... | genres | production_countries | ... | total_pages

Thanks — the problem is simple:
In some rows, origin_country is a character string; in others, it's a list. bind_rows() cannot combine a character column with a list column.

You don't need to fix this in get_movie_details().
Just delete the origin_country column after collecting all data.

✅ Solution:

After you run your lapply() or purrr::map_dfr():

r
all_details <- lapply(movie_ids, get_movie_details) %>%
  bind_rows()

# Remove origin_country after collection
all_details <- all_details %>% select(-origin_country)

🔧 Why this works:

  • select(-origin_country) drops the column after binding, so you avoid the type conflict.

  • It’s clean, safe, and doesn't touch your request code.

🔥 If you want to force it earlier (alternative):

If you want to color only China and the US, you can create a new variable in your dataframe to control colors explicitly. Here's how you do it:

✅ Example:

1️⃣ Create a highlight_country column

r
count_countries <- count_countries %>%
  mutate(highlight_country = ifelse(production_countries %in% c("China", "United States of America"),
                                    production_countries, "Other"))

2️⃣ Plot with color = highlight_country

r
p_countries <- count_countries %>% 
  filter(!is.na(production_countries)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = num, group = production_countries, color = highlight_country)) +
  geom_point(size = 1, alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(
    x = "Year",
    y = "Number of movies made",
    color = NULL
  ) +
  geom_text(data = count_countries %>%
              filter(production_countries %in% c("China", "United States of America")),
            aes(label = production_countries), hjust = -0.2, vjust = -0.2)

3️⃣ Optional: Set specific colors for clarity

r
p_countries +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(
    "China" = "red",
    "United States of America" = "blue",
    "Other" = "grey80"
  ))

🔑 Why this works:

  • highlight_country splits the groups into "China", "United States of America", and "Other".

  • Only "China" and "United States of America" get distinct colors.

  • scale_color_manual() lets you pick the colors explicitly.

Here's how you can explicitly:

  1. Set color for "China" and "United States of America" vs "Other".

✅ Example:

1️⃣ Modify highlight_country as before:

r
count_countries <- count_countries %>%
  mutate(highlight_country = ifelse(production_countries %in% c("China", "United States of America"),
                                    production_countries, "Other"))

2️⃣ Map both color and alpha:

r
p_countries <- count_countries %>% 
  filter(!is.na(production_countries)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = num, group = production_countries, 
             color = highlight_country, alpha = highlight_country)) +
  geom_point(size = 1) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(
    x = "Year",
    y = "Number of movies made",
    color = NULL,
    alpha = NULL
  ) +
  geom_text(data = count_countries %>%
              filter(production_countries %in% c("China", "United States of America")),
            aes(label = production_countries), hjust = -0.2, vjust = -0.2)

3️⃣ Set both color and alpha manually:

r
p_countries +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(
    "China" = "red",
    "United States of America" = "blue",
    "Other" = "grey80"
  )) +
  scale_alpha_manual(values = c(
    "China" = 1,
    "United States of America" = 1,
    "Other" = 0.3
  ))

🔑 Why this works:

  • highlight_country controls both color and alpha.

  • scale_color_manual() gives explicit colors.

  • scale_alpha_manual() lets you reduce alpha for "Other" without affecting the main two countries.
